t the heart of jurisprudence. For example, what role do emotions ranging from disgust to compassion play in the decision-making processes of judges, lawyers, juries, and clients? What emotions belong in which legal contexts? Is there a hierarchy of emotions, and, if so, through what sources do we identify it? To what extent are emotions subject to change or tutelage? How can we evaluate the role of emotion in such disparate contexts as death sentencing, laws about same sex marriage, hate crime legislation, punitive damages or shaming penalties? Consisting of original essays by leading scholars of law, theology, political science, and philosophy, The Passions of Law contributes to ongoing efforts to humanize law and reveals how this previously unacknowledged aspect of decision-making exerts a much greater impact on justice and the practice of law than most tend, or like, to think. Learn more about Susan Bandes  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aEmotions. 0aLawxPsychological aspects. 7aLAW / Essays.2bisacsh1 aAllen, Danielle S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBandes, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBandes, Susan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCalhoun, Cheshire, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeigh, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKahan, Dan M, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMassaro, Toni M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiller, William Ian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMinow, Martha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMurphy, Jeffrie G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabul